Limit of Panic
COPENHAGEN – We often hear that the world as we know it will face Armageddon, usually in the form of ecological collapse.
In fact, the basic idea has been with us since the Club of Rome's seminal 1972 warning, "The Limits to Growth."
But time is not patient.
The 1972 "Limits to Growth" warned humanity that a catastrophic collapse was imminent.
However, we saw financial panics thereafter, without any real shortages or production collapses.
Instead, the resources created by human ingenuity more than suffice to meet human consumption.
But the basic idea of The Limits to Growth still holds: We continue a trend, focusing on misleading solutions to minor issues while ignoring major problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, techno-optimism waned, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book Silent Spring ignited fears about pollution and sparked the modern environmental movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title The Population Bomb summed it up.
In the first Earth Day of 1970, people were overwhelmingly pessimistic.
The Limits to Growth was intended to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people want to consume too much.
Even if our genius buys us some time, we will ultimately destroy the planet and ourselves with pollution.
The only hope is to slow down economic growth itself, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a significantly poorer level than now.
This view still resonates today, despite being fundamentally wrong.
For example, the authors of The Limits of Growth predicted that by 2013, the world would have exhausted reserves of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc.
Yet, even though commodity prices have recently rebounded somewhat, they remain at only about a third of their levels from 150 years ago.
Technological innovations replaced mercury in batteries, dental amalgams, and thermometers, and by 2000, mercury consumption had fallen by 98%, while prices had dropped by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, supplies of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc have consistently exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical extraction technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were expected to be depleted in 1990 and 1992, respectively; now, reserves of both exceed their 1970 levels despite a massive increase in our consumption.
In just the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled America's potential natural gas resource base and halved its price.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP this century will increase 14-fold, with developing countries increasing 24-fold.
The Limits to Growth got it wrong because its authors overlooked the greatest resource of all: our own ingenuity.
Population growth began slowing in the 1960s.
Food supply has not collapsed (there are 1.5 billion hectares of arable land in use, plus an additional 2.7 billion hectares in reserve).
Nutrition deficiencies have been halved, dropping from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
We have also managed pollution.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past when we had no air pollution from particulate matter, and were all happy farmers, and a future where smokestacks from heaters would make us unable to breathe. Reality is the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, yet nearly three million people — equivalent to one in every 500 people — died annually due to air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Now, the ratio has fallen to one death for every 2,000 people.
Although pollution still kills more people than malaria, its fatality rate is declining rather than rising.
Nevertheless, the ideas sown by The Limits to Growth continue to shape the thoughts of both the public and the elites.
Take recycling, for instance, which is usually more a feel-good gesture than a genuinely effective way to protect the environment.
For example, paper usually comes from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
Programs related to paper recycling and government subsidies result in low-quality paper, while they protect resources that are not threatened.
Similarly, policies such as China's family planning and India's mandatory sterilization, which were concerned about overpopulation leading to self-destruction.
In addition, despite the fact that pesticides and other pollutants are believed to kill half of humanity, good pesticide regulation results in only 20 annual deaths in the United States, while the use of pesticides creates cheaper and more abundant food supplies.
Factually, relying solely on organic agriculture – the movement spurred by fear of pesticides – would impose an additional cost of $100 billion annually on the U.S.
Agricultural efficiency will decrease by 16%, requiring an additional 65 million hectares of farmland – half the size of modern-day California – to maintain current output.
The rise in prices will lead to reduced consumption of fruits and vegetables, resulting in serious negative health impacts (including thousands of additional cancer deaths annually).
Being fixated on gloomy scenarios prevents us from addressing the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, causing the death of 15 million people annually – a quarter of all deaths – from diseases that are easily treatable.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people rise out of poverty, most can afford to bear the burden of preventing infectious diseases.
Over the past three decades, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world in reducing the number of poor people by nearly one billion.
This has resulted in widespread improvements in health, lifespan, and quality of life.
The forty-year history since the release of "The Limits to Growth" shows that we need more, not less, growth.
Expanding trade is estimated to bring annual benefits of over $100 trillion by the end of this century, far surpassing the meager gains from fear-mongering and risk-averse "feel-good" policies.
This requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our infinite potential to create a brighter future.
